+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XtQZ6HHcF7cCEjKuJQMqdH","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have a complete picture of the codebase. Let me provide you with a comprehensive overview:\n\n---\n\n## Complete Codebase Structure and Requirements\n\n### Project Overview\n\nThis is a **Task Queue System** implementation project - building a fully-featured in-memory task queue system that grows incrementally through 12 phases. The system is similar to Bull, BeeQueue, or Celery but entirely in-memory with no external dependencies.\n\n### Directory Structure\n\n```\n/workspace/\n├── .git/                    # Git repository\n├── src/                     # Source code directory (empty, .gitkeep only)\n├── phases/                  # 12 phase requirement files\n│   ├── phase-01.md\n│   ├── phase-02.md\n│   ├── ...\n│   └── phase-12.md\n├── package.json             # NPM configuration\n├── tsconfig.json            # TypeScript configuration\n├── vitest.config.ts         # Test framework configuration\n├── .eslintrc.cjs            # ESLint configuration\n└── TASK.md                  # Main task overview\n```\n\n### Configuration Files\n\n**package.json:**\n- Name: `bench-task-queue`\n- Type: ES module\n- Scripts: `build` (tsc), `lint` (eslint), `test` (vitest run)\n- DevDependencies: TypeScript 5.4, ESLint, Vitest, Node types\n\n**tsconfig.json:**\n- Target: ES2022\n- Module: Node16\n- Strict mode enabled\n- Output to `./dist`, root is `./src`\n- Declarations and source maps enabled\n\n**vitest.config.ts:**\n- Global test utilities enabled\n- 10-second test timeout\n\n**.eslintrc.cjs:**\n- TypeScript parser with strict recommended rules\n- Node.js and ES2022 environment\n- Custom rule: unused variables allowed with `_` prefix\n\n---\n\n## All 12 Phase Requirements (Complete Details)\n\n### Phase 1: Basic FIFO Queue\n**Goal:** Implement core task queue functionality\n\n- Tasks have unique identifiers (UUID), status, and creation timestamp\n- New tasks start in \"pending\" state\n- Queue operates FIFO (first-in, first-out)\n- Retrieving next task returns oldest pending task → transitions to \"processing\"\n- If no tasks available, retrieval returns `null`\n- Must track waiting task count\n\n### Phase 2: Named Queues\n**Goal:** Support multiple independent queues\n\n- Tasks added to named queues (default queue if no name given)\n- Each queue operates independently\n- Implicit queue creation on first task addition\n- API backward-compatible with Phase 1\n- Must list all existing queue names\n- Non-existent or empty queue returns `null` on retrieval\n\n### Phase 3: Priority\n**Goal:** Process urgent tasks first\n\n- Priority levels 1-10 (1=highest, 10=lowest), default=5\n- Higher-priority (lower number) tasks retrieved first\n- Same priority → FIFO order\n- Invalid priorities cause error\n- Priority per-queue\n- Task object exposes priority level\n\n### Phase 4: Delayed and Scheduled Tasks\n**Goal:** Defer task availability to future times\n\n- Tasks can have delay (milliseconds) or specific future availability time\n- Delayed tasks added immediately but not returned until available\n- Non-delayed tasks preferred over unavailable delayed tasks\n- Multiple simultaneous available tasks ordered by: availability time → priority → FIFO\n- Task object shows availability time\n- Works with named queues\n\n### Phase 5: Retry with Backoff\n**Goal:** Automatic retry on failure with exponential backoff\n\n- Mark tasks as completed or failed\n- Failed tasks with retries remaining re-added with delay\n- Exponential backoff: `baseDelay * 2^(attempt - 1)` (e.g., 1s, 2s, 4s, ...)\n- Default max retries: 3 (configurable per task)\n- Default base delay: 1000ms (configurable per task)\n- Track attempt count per task\n- Retried tasks keep original queue and priority\n- Exhausted retries → task in failed state\n\n### Phase 6: Dead Letter Queue\n**Goal:** Permanent storage for failed tasks\n\n- Tasks exhausting retries moved to dead letter queue (DLQ)\n- Each named queue has independent DLQ\n- View all dead-lettered tasks for queue\n- Dead-lettered tasks retain error info and failure count\n- Ability to retry dead-lettered tasks back to original queue\n- Ability to clear DLQ for queue\n\n### Phase 7: Task Dependencies\n**Goal:** Conditional task processing based on prerequisites\n\n- Tasks can declare dependencies on other task IDs\n- Task with unresolved dependencies is blocked (not returned)\n- When dependency completes, check for now-unblocked tasks\n- Circular dependencies detected and rejected at creation time\n- Depending on non-existent task → error\n- Failed dependency does NOT fail dependents (remains blocked)\n- Inspect task dependency status\n\n### Phase 8: Concurrency Control\n**Goal:** Limit simultaneous task processing per queue\n\n- Each queue has configurable max concurrency limit\n- If limit reached, retrieval returns `null` even with pending tasks\n- Completing/failing task frees concurrency slot\n- Default: no limit (unlimited)\n- Query concurrency limit and current active count\n- Concurrency respects priority ordering\n\n### Phase 9: Progress Tracking and Cancellation\n**Goal:** Monitor task progress and enable cancellation\n\n- Processing task can report progress (0-100%) with optional message\n- Query task's current progress\n- Subscribe to progress updates with notifications on change\n- Subscriptions are cancellable\n- Cancel pending or processing tasks\n- Cancelled pending tasks removed from queue\n- Cancelled processing tasks status updated\n- Cancelled tasks never retried\n\n### Phase 10: Recurring Tasks\n**Goal:** Scheduled task creation via cron expressions\n\n- Schedule associates cron expression with queue and task template\n- Simple cron support:\n  - `*/N * * * *` – every N minutes\n  - `0 * * * *` – every hour on the hour\n  - `0 0 * * *` – every day at midnight\n- Create, remove, list schedules\n- Manual \"tick\"/\"check\" mechanism for testing\n- Once enqueued, recurring tasks are regular tasks\n- Removing schedule stops future occurrences\n\n### Phase 11: Middleware Pipeline\n**Goal:** Intercept and transform task processing\n\n- Middleware functions registered per queue\n- Task passes through all middleware in order before handler\n- Each middleware receives task and \"next\" function\n- Not calling \"next\" skips processing\n- Middleware can modify task\n- Middleware errors mark task as failed\n- Processing handler registered per queue (invoked after middleware)\n- Each queue has independent middleware stack\n\n### Phase 12: Graceful Shutdown\n**Goal:** Orderly system wind-down\n\n- Shutdown signals system to stop accepting new tasks\n- Adding tasks after shutdown causes error\n- Waits for processing tasks to finish (configurable timeout)\n- Forces cancellation if timeout exceeded\n- Register callbacks to run during shutdown\n- Produces summary: completed tasks, force-cancelled tasks, shutdown duration\n- Multiple shutdown calls safe and idempotent\n- Completes immediately if no processing tasks\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n**Key Constraints:**\n- No external runtime dependencies allowed\n- All code in `src/` directory\n- Main API exported from `src/index.ts`\n- Must pass TypeScript strict mode compilation\n- Must pass ESLint validation\n- Tests written with Vitest\n\n**Design Considerations:**\n- Later phases force rethinking early decisions - design for extensibility\n- Tasks need unique identifiers and lifecycle status tracking\n- Features (priorities, delays, dependencies) interact with each other\n- Per-queue configuration and independence critical\n- Error handling and state consistency essential across all phases"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1f38c2 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 19095\ntool_uses: 21\nduration_ms: 32121</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f6967678-3822-4f89-ab38-0f49af66af26